sopotamia, Ancient Greece, the Roman Empire, China, European colonialism, Central America, and the American push westward. We see how soil has shaped us and we have shaped soil-as society after society has risen, prospered, and plowed through a natural endowment of fertile dirt. David R. Montgomery sees in the recent rise of organic and no-till farming the hope for a new agricultural revolution that might help us avoid the fate of previous civilizations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aSoil erosion. 0aSoil sciencexHistory. 0aSoils. 4aagrarian society. 4aagricultural. 4aamerican push westward. 4aancient greece. 4aanthropologist. 4aanthropology. 4aarchaeologists. 4aarchaeology. 4acentral america. 4achina. 4acolonialism. 4acultural and historical context. 4aeuropean colonialism. 4ageographer. 4ageography. 4ageologist. 4ageology. 4ahistory of. 4aimportance of dirt. 4amesopotamia. 4aprotective vegetation. 4aroman empire. 4arunning out of dirt. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520952119423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520952119.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles